1
00:00:17,434 --> 00:00:19,175
My name is Federico Alvarez.

2
00:00:19,269 --> 00:00:22,933
I'm one of the screenwriters
and the producer of this movie.

3
00:00:23,023 --> 00:00:27,392
I'm Rodo Sayagues,
screenwriter and director.

4
00:00:27,486 --> 00:00:31,855
And I'm Pedro Luque,
I'm the director of photography.

5
00:00:31,949 --> 00:00:35,283
[Sayagues] And we're going
to watch the movie with you

6
00:00:35,369 --> 00:00:42,116
and tell you a bit about the anecdotes
and what this movie meant for us.

7
00:00:42,793 --> 00:00:44,033
[Alvarez] We're from Uruguay.

8
00:00:44,127 --> 00:00:48,963
We did this in Spanish,
to do it in our native language

9
00:00:49,049 --> 00:00:52,633
so it would be more natural,
but also to give an alternate version

10
00:00:52,719 --> 00:00:57,054
of the commentary done by Rodo in English,
which I'm sure you can find somewhere.

11
00:00:57,140 --> 00:01:02,977
The fist logo of our company, Bad Hombre,
the production company.

12
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:06,806
This is the first movie under that logo.

13
00:01:08,402 --> 00:01:09,938
[Sayagues] Well, let's begin.

14
00:01:11,321 --> 00:01:16,487
-[Luque] The majestic city of Detroit.
-[Sayagues] Exactly.

15
00:01:16,577 --> 00:01:21,447
[Alvarez] This take was an attempt...

16
00:01:21,540 --> 00:01:23,998
It represents the first movie well.

17
00:01:24,084 --> 00:01:29,375
On the first one, we started with Pedro,
we did the aerial take,

18
00:01:29,464 --> 00:01:31,171
but this one is more sophisticated.

19
00:01:31,258 --> 00:01:32,544
[chuckling]

20
00:01:32,634 --> 00:01:36,298
[Luque] It's an homage to the first one
and an introduction to the same world.

21
00:01:37,180 --> 00:01:38,921
[Alvarez] More special effects.

22
00:01:39,766 --> 00:01:45,227
A girl walking in 3D.
Tell us, Rodo, why is the girl in 3D?

23
00:01:45,314 --> 00:01:46,725
[Sayagues] Why is the girl in 3D?

24
00:01:46,815 --> 00:01:49,102
Well, because she's three years old

25
00:01:50,152 --> 00:01:56,489
and it was literally impossible
for her to do that, so...

26
00:01:56,575 --> 00:02:00,409
[Alvarez] Besides, I imagine you'd be...
For how long were you filming in Detroit?

27
00:02:00,495 --> 00:02:02,156
-[Sayagues] One day.
-[Alvarez] Right, one day.

28
00:02:02,247 --> 00:02:05,456
-[Sayagues] Two days, right? One or two.
-[Luque] One or two days.

29
00:02:05,542 --> 00:02:07,124
[Alvarez] Well, here they are in...

30
00:02:07,794 --> 00:02:12,789
[Luque] Here we are in
the middle of Serbia, in a remote forest.

31
00:02:12,883 --> 00:02:14,339
[Alvarez] What's that?

32
00:02:14,426 --> 00:02:16,463
[Sayagues] Nobody was able
to tell us what that was,

33
00:02:16,553 --> 00:02:20,592
but we thought it would be good
to include it in the scene.

34
00:02:20,682 --> 00:02:22,093
[Luque] Especially keeping in mind

35
00:02:22,184 --> 00:02:26,974
the apocalyptic or semi-apocalyptic world
of Don't Breathe.

36
00:02:27,064 --> 00:02:30,056
[Alvarez] I imagine it's some sort of--
It looks like a generator, right?

37
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:31,311
Like some type of generator.

38
00:02:31,401 --> 00:02:34,519
[Luque] I think it was from a water
treatment plant or something like that.

39
00:02:35,113 --> 00:02:36,399
[Sayagues] I think the idea was...

40
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:40,199
we're opening with a scene
that takes place in a forest,

41
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:45,530
to include elements that will help us make
the transition from forest to city,

42
00:02:45,624 --> 00:02:50,369
even if it's a city
half swallowed by nature...

43
00:02:51,630 --> 00:02:53,997
and it looks like a city
in the middle of a jungle.

44
00:02:54,091 --> 00:02:57,129
But the idea was that,
to urbanize that forest.

45
00:02:57,219 --> 00:02:59,085
Also this,
the basketball hoop in the background,

46
00:02:59,179 --> 00:03:01,011
elements that bring you
slowly to the city.

47
00:03:01,098 --> 00:03:07,185
[Alvarez] Correct. Because originally,
in the script, it was like an auto plant.

48
00:03:07,270 --> 00:03:11,264
I think the first version we wrote
was an auto plant, right?

49
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:16,944
[Sayagues] Yes, as a matter of fact
it does have the spirit of a junkyard.

50
00:03:17,030 --> 00:03:18,646
[Luque] It's Detroit.

51
00:03:18,740 --> 00:03:24,326
When we went to Detroit, we noticed
that there were rotten cars all over.

52
00:03:24,413 --> 00:03:27,906
[Alvarez] And we were thinking
of creating the climax of the movie

53
00:03:27,999 --> 00:03:30,912
in the same auto plant at a given time.

54
00:03:31,002 --> 00:03:33,243
We thought that what would happen
in the third act

55
00:03:33,338 --> 00:03:37,002
was that they would leave home and
they would get to the abandoned factory.

56
00:03:37,092 --> 00:03:41,086
But then we thought about how many movies
are set in an abandoned car factory.

57
00:03:41,179 --> 00:03:42,465
[chuckling]

58
00:03:42,556 --> 00:03:43,762
How could we do that?

59
00:03:43,849 --> 00:03:48,935
[Sayagues] Stephen Lang appears here,
the Blind Man.

60
00:03:49,896 --> 00:03:52,763
[Alvarez] Was this the first time
you filmed him in character?

61
00:03:52,858 --> 00:03:56,271
[Luque] No. We did a screen test
which was brutal.

62
00:03:56,361 --> 00:03:59,649
That's where he shows up for
the first time, but it's not in the movie.

63
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:02,607
For us, that was the moment
we saw him be reborn.

64
00:04:02,701 --> 00:04:06,285
-[Alvarez] Reborn.
-[Sayagues] Yes, that was exciting.

65
00:04:07,706 --> 00:04:10,744
[Luque] This shot is in Detroit.
This shot-- No. This shot is also...

66
00:04:10,834 --> 00:04:12,290
[Sayagues] It's half Detroit, half Serbia.

67
00:04:12,377 --> 00:04:14,334
[Luque] Half Detroit, half Serbia, right.

68
00:04:14,421 --> 00:04:16,788
-This house is...
-[Alvarez] Which half?

69
00:04:16,882 --> 00:04:19,374
[Sayagues] That part with the forest
below, that's in Serbia.

70
00:04:19,468 --> 00:04:21,880
[Luque] And the house.
And the top part is Detroit.

71
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:24,257
[Alvarez] But the house was 3D.

72
00:04:24,347 --> 00:04:25,963
[Sayagues] It's 3D. The house is 3D.

73
00:04:26,057 --> 00:04:29,391
[Luque] We built the house, the next shot,
the ones that come after.

74
00:04:29,478 --> 00:04:31,435
[Alvarez] You can tell
there was a real house,

75
00:04:31,521 --> 00:04:34,980
but I remember seeing the shot
without a house.

76
00:04:35,066 --> 00:04:36,727
I thought it was Detroit.

77
00:04:36,818 --> 00:04:40,277
[Sayagues] The shot without a house
is in Detroit.

78
00:04:40,363 --> 00:04:41,444
[Luque] Here we are.

79
00:04:41,531 --> 00:04:43,238
[Alvarez] This was one of
the first scenes we filmed.

80
00:04:43,325 --> 00:04:44,156
[Luque] Yes.

81
00:04:44,242 --> 00:04:45,607
[Sayagues] This was the first day filming.

82
00:04:45,702 --> 00:04:48,364
It was my first day of filming
as a director. I was pretty nervous.

83
00:04:48,455 --> 00:04:51,038
[Luque] Of movies.
We had done several commercials.

84
00:04:51,124 --> 00:04:53,582
-[Sayagues] Everyone was nervous.
-[Alvarez] I was nervous, too.

85
00:04:53,668 --> 00:04:57,206
I remember that it was
the first daily I saw from home.

86
00:04:57,297 --> 00:04:59,413
During the pandemic,
you were making the movie

87
00:04:59,508 --> 00:05:03,046
and I was here, at home,
and I hit play and started watching.

88
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:05,548
And I remember saying,
"Fantastic! It looks like a movie!"

89
00:05:05,639 --> 00:05:06,970
[Sayagues] "Not too bad."

90
00:05:08,350 --> 00:05:11,308
[Luque] The tender moment between...

91
00:05:11,394 --> 00:05:14,386
The guy is still a toughie.

92
00:05:14,481 --> 00:05:17,314
[Sayagues] I also remember
that we talked a lot

93
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:20,893
about the idea of starting filming
with this scene

94
00:05:20,987 --> 00:05:26,528
because it was a scene
that required a lot of Madelyn,

95
00:05:26,618 --> 00:05:28,450
playing the role of Phoenix,

96
00:05:28,537 --> 00:05:31,825
and she was nervous as well
about having to start with a scene

97
00:05:31,915 --> 00:05:35,033
where she was the protagonist.
But the truth is she did very well.

98
00:05:35,627 --> 00:05:38,540
[Luque] You can read the hat, right?

99
00:05:38,630 --> 00:05:41,839
[Alvarez] Yes, man. Shameless advertising.

100
00:05:41,925 --> 00:05:42,915
[Sayagues chuckles]

101
00:05:43,009 --> 00:05:44,591
[Luque] We had to put something.

102
00:05:46,388 --> 00:05:48,880
[Alvarez] It was Stephanie's first movie,
like we said before.

103
00:05:50,767 --> 00:05:53,384
[Luque] This is in the study,
the close-up of the girl.

104
00:05:53,478 --> 00:05:55,469
[Sayagues]
It's also Madelyn's first movie.

105
00:05:56,481 --> 00:05:57,721
I said no.

106
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:05,196
[Alvarez] This was interesting,
the idea of the blind man's only friend.

107
00:06:05,282 --> 00:06:09,697
The only person who, more or less,
dares to say something to the blind man.

108
00:06:09,786 --> 00:06:11,652
When I saw it,
I thought this shot looked great,

109
00:06:11,746 --> 00:06:13,487
with the reflection
of the blind man there.

110
00:06:13,582 --> 00:06:15,414
It was longer in the first cut,

111
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:17,958
where there was a bit more
of the guy's reflection.

112
00:06:18,044 --> 00:06:20,376
We cut this scene quite a bit.
It used to be...

113
00:06:20,463 --> 00:06:23,546
[Luque] This was one of the few scenes
we reshot some things for, right, Rodo?

114
00:06:23,633 --> 00:06:24,714
[Sayagues] Yes.

115
00:06:24,801 --> 00:06:27,168
[Luque] After filming,
we realized some shots were missing.

116
00:06:27,262 --> 00:06:30,675
It was much more complex
and ended up looking simpler

117
00:06:30,765 --> 00:06:32,676
in the final edit, and it works perfectly.

118
00:06:32,767 --> 00:06:34,804
[Sayagues]
But we used that shot we missed.

119
00:06:34,895 --> 00:06:36,511
We made it better in the same shot.

120
00:06:36,605 --> 00:06:38,221
[Luque] Yes, yes. A couple of days later.

121
00:06:38,315 --> 00:06:40,898
[Sayagues] A couple of days later
we said we were missing a shot.

122
00:06:40,984 --> 00:06:42,691
Then we shot this one
and ended up using it.

123
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:45,937
[Luque] I just noticed there's a sign
that says "underpass.”

124
00:06:46,031 --> 00:06:48,113
That was added in post, right?

125
00:06:48,199 --> 00:06:50,031
-[Alvarez] Yes.
-[Sayagues] No, we placed it there.

126
00:06:50,118 --> 00:06:52,200
-[Luque] We did?
-[Sayagues] Really.

127
00:06:55,665 --> 00:07:00,660
[Alvarez] Madelyn was in
the first casting.

128
00:07:00,754 --> 00:07:02,586
[Sayagues] Yes, yes.

129
00:07:02,672 --> 00:07:04,504
I think my mom sang it to me
when I was little.

130
00:07:04,591 --> 00:07:06,423
[Alvarez] She was there
early in the process.

131
00:07:06,509 --> 00:07:07,715
[Sayagues] Yes. Right away.

132
00:07:07,802 --> 00:07:09,088
You wanna pay her a visit?

133
00:07:09,179 --> 00:07:11,045
[Alvarez] And she had not
made movies, only TV.

134
00:07:11,139 --> 00:07:16,976
[Sayagues] No, some TV shows,
but never a movie.

135
00:07:17,062 --> 00:07:18,678
But she did great.

136
00:07:20,774 --> 00:07:22,606
-This is Detroit.
-[Luque] Back in Detroit.

137
00:07:23,401 --> 00:07:29,647
We had to find identical trucks
in Detroit and another in Belgrade.

138
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:32,611
[Sayagues]
This ended up looking very nice.

139
00:07:32,702 --> 00:07:38,323
And these ashes that float,
I remember that it was Fede's idea.

140
00:07:38,416 --> 00:07:41,374
A few days before filming he said,
"Are they going to have ashes floating?"

141
00:07:41,461 --> 00:07:42,792
And I said, "What ashes?"

142
00:07:42,879 --> 00:07:45,746
And the truth is without those ashes,
the scene...

143
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:48,298
[Luque] It gives it a certain magic.

144
00:07:48,385 --> 00:07:49,420
[Alvarez] In Evil Dead,

145
00:07:49,511 --> 00:07:52,048
I remember the first time
the cabin door opens, it's the same.

146
00:07:52,138 --> 00:07:56,348
I don't know where I saw it,
but I remember asking for it.

147
00:07:56,434 --> 00:07:58,596
They had this technique with a mop.

148
00:07:58,687 --> 00:08:02,806
-One of those sticks with a thing.
-[Luque] Mop.

149
00:08:02,899 --> 00:08:07,439
[Alvarez] They came with the thing
and shook it in front of the lighting,

150
00:08:07,529 --> 00:08:10,066
they kept going and then, "Action!"

151
00:08:10,156 --> 00:08:13,365
[Luque] This time they used
what they call stone candles.

152
00:08:13,451 --> 00:08:16,443
Remember?
The ones we used in Spider's Web.

153
00:08:19,457 --> 00:08:25,203
[Alvarez] I love this,
without any subtlety we planted it there.

154
00:08:25,296 --> 00:08:27,788
[Sayagues] It must be said,
this is a cardinal sin

155
00:08:27,882 --> 00:08:31,591
for screenwriters to place exposition
on a TV that is just...

156
00:08:31,678 --> 00:08:35,091
[Alvarez] Of course. Most of the people
who are watching this with the comments

157
00:08:35,181 --> 00:08:36,467
have already seen the movie.

158
00:08:36,558 --> 00:08:38,640
People already know how the film ends.

159
00:08:38,727 --> 00:08:39,467
Upon second viewing, you realize
that here, in the first few minutes,

160
00:08:39,477 --> 00:08:41,969
Upon second viewing, you realize
that here, in the first few minutes,

161
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:45,601
they're already telling you
where the plot is going. [laughs]

162
00:08:45,692 --> 00:08:49,310
The secret twist of the third act
is already there.

163
00:08:50,530 --> 00:08:55,400
The story changed in editing.

164
00:08:56,578 --> 00:08:58,660
Obviously,
the original scene was like this.

165
00:08:58,747 --> 00:09:01,580
She would come and do all this
in the script, when we wrote it.

166
00:09:01,666 --> 00:09:06,001
Later we realized in editing
that it worked better

167
00:09:06,087 --> 00:09:10,081
if we saw the scene,
but then we pushed it back

168
00:09:10,175 --> 00:09:12,883
and made it feel
like it was all a daydream,

169
00:09:12,969 --> 00:09:14,300
like she was dreaming.

170
00:09:14,387 --> 00:09:18,130
[Luque] We also gave it
a more saturated look.

171
00:09:18,224 --> 00:09:20,807
[Alvarez] All the colors go up
and then get pushed back.

172
00:09:21,728 --> 00:09:23,059
Really good effects.

173
00:09:23,146 --> 00:09:26,013
You have to give credit
to all those people,

174
00:09:26,107 --> 00:09:30,192
because they did all this,
Aparato did all this.

175
00:09:30,278 --> 00:09:32,315
[Sayagues] This is a location in Serbia.

176
00:09:32,405 --> 00:09:37,400
Everything was built,
except the background.

177
00:09:37,494 --> 00:09:42,364
The city in the background
was done by Aparato, in a very good way.

178
00:09:42,457 --> 00:09:47,748
[Alvarez] You can't see the chroma.
You can't see the blue screen at all.

179
00:09:49,255 --> 00:09:51,587
-[Sayagues] It feels like Detroit.
-[Alvarez] Totally.

180
00:09:51,674 --> 00:09:56,089
There is a section of Detroit
that looks exactly like this.

181
00:09:56,179 --> 00:09:58,796
[Luque] Yes, we stopped
on a street in Detroit...

182
00:09:58,890 --> 00:10:03,805
[Alvarez] For a public bathroom
in Detroit, the floor is pretty clean.

183
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:07,179
[Luque] They swept it.
It's a family place.

184
00:10:07,273 --> 00:10:08,934
[laughter]

185
00:10:09,025 --> 00:10:11,608
-[Sayagues] I really like this shot.
-[Alvarez] This shot is great.

186
00:10:11,694 --> 00:10:14,857
It was one of the first shots I saw
and said, "Good, they're making a movie."

187
00:10:14,948 --> 00:10:16,814
[Sayagues] They're filmmaking.

188
00:10:16,908 --> 00:10:18,740
[Luque] It looks nice on the big screen.

189
00:10:19,410 --> 00:10:21,151
[Sayagues] This is the shot
I like the most.

190
00:10:21,246 --> 00:10:22,407
[Luque] This is Rodo's shot.

191
00:10:22,497 --> 00:10:23,987
[Sayagues] I don't know why,
but I like it.

192
00:10:24,082 --> 00:10:26,323
[Luque] This is your shot,
you planned it, envisioned it.

193
00:10:26,417 --> 00:10:28,624
We had the mirror made
with those dimensions.

194
00:10:28,711 --> 00:10:33,547
[Sayagues] And with the red wall behind,
because we thought, with great aspiration,

195
00:10:33,633 --> 00:10:38,048
we thought later in the film
we would find out

196
00:10:38,138 --> 00:10:42,382
the two of them were related
with blood ties that united them.

197
00:10:42,475 --> 00:10:44,807
And the red line in the middle
which linked the two of them

198
00:10:44,894 --> 00:10:46,259
seemed like fun to us.

199
00:10:51,568 --> 00:10:53,150
[Alvarez] This man is great.

200
00:10:53,903 --> 00:10:57,612
It's like he's excited
to see his daughter for the first time.

201
00:10:57,699 --> 00:10:59,315
Like he wants to hug her.

202
00:10:59,409 --> 00:11:00,945
[Sayagues] That finger is me.

203
00:11:01,035 --> 00:11:02,525
[laughter]

204
00:11:03,371 --> 00:11:06,329
Yes, Brendan is a great actor

205
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:11,877
and it was hard to play that role
because it has many different sides

206
00:11:11,963 --> 00:11:15,456
and you can tell he was excited
to see her for the first time.

207
00:11:16,050 --> 00:11:18,087
-[car door closes]
-[tinkling]

208
00:11:18,178 --> 00:11:19,464
You okay?

209
00:11:20,096 --> 00:11:24,431
[Alvarez] The anamorphic lenses
they chose are amazing.

210
00:11:24,517 --> 00:11:29,227
In the previous shot,
you can clearly see it on the left.

211
00:11:29,314 --> 00:11:30,770
[Luque] You can see the deformation.

212
00:11:30,857 --> 00:11:33,394
[Alvarez] Pedro, explain those lenses.
Why do they look all deformed?

213
00:11:33,484 --> 00:11:37,398
[Luque] Because it's a lens
that compresses the image laterally.

214
00:11:37,488 --> 00:11:42,483
So, if you look closely,
out of focus they have an oval shape,

215
00:11:43,161 --> 00:11:46,404
because what it does...
It's an old cinema invention.

216
00:11:46,497 --> 00:11:48,579
It compresses the image laterally

217
00:11:48,666 --> 00:11:52,500
so it fits into a small square
on the screen, and then it's stretched.

218
00:11:53,421 --> 00:11:55,753
[Sayagues] This looks great to me.
It was a very wise decision,

219
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,956
because it gives the whole movie

220
00:11:58,051 --> 00:12:01,419
a feeling that this is not exactly
the real world,

221
00:12:01,512 --> 00:12:05,847
that this takes place in the dimension
of dreams, of nightmares.

222
00:12:05,934 --> 00:12:08,847
But it's something very dreamlike
which separates it from the real world

223
00:12:08,937 --> 00:12:11,395
and allows the fable
to make more sense as well.

224
00:12:11,481 --> 00:12:15,645
[Luque] Of course.
That's the famous made-up world.

225
00:12:15,735 --> 00:12:18,102
[Sayagues] And it also allows us
to do what we want

226
00:12:18,196 --> 00:12:21,154
where we create the things we want,

227
00:12:21,241 --> 00:12:25,485
