920
00:51:03,727 --> 00:51:05,343
on a certain level,

921
00:51:06,105 --> 00:51:09,894
if there's something he loves,
it's animals, he's a dog lover.

922
00:51:09,984 --> 00:51:11,315
[Luque] Sure.

923
00:51:11,402 --> 00:51:13,268
[screaming]

924
00:51:13,362 --> 00:51:15,069
Phoenix!

925
00:51:16,073 --> 00:51:18,235
Well, he took her.

926
00:51:20,911 --> 00:51:22,902
He listens. He's got a fine ear.

927
00:51:24,873 --> 00:51:27,080
[Alvarez] For Raul,
this is his first scene,

928
00:51:27,167 --> 00:51:29,033
and then you realize he's not a bad guy.

929
00:51:29,128 --> 00:51:32,541
He does it carefully, with compassion.

930
00:51:36,051 --> 00:51:39,794
I loved that in the script,

931
00:51:39,888 --> 00:51:44,303
the way in which he was going to cross
to the other side and leave the dog caged.

932
00:51:44,393 --> 00:51:47,351
[Sayagues] That metal frame
was really heavy,

933
00:51:47,438 --> 00:51:51,477
remember, super heavy,
and Slang lifted it like it was nothing.

934
00:51:51,567 --> 00:51:54,650
[Luque] It was something
totally custom made,

935
00:51:54,737 --> 00:51:56,319
because such a thing didn't exist.

936
00:51:56,405 --> 00:52:00,114
It was something we had in mind,

937
00:52:00,200 --> 00:52:02,612
but it didn't have an equivalent
in real life.

938
00:52:14,590 --> 00:52:15,751
[Sayagues] Raylan.

939
00:52:16,884 --> 00:52:19,501
They had this all planned out, I think.

940
00:52:20,554 --> 00:52:22,966
[Luque] Where's the cooler?
Didn't they carry organs?

941
00:52:23,057 --> 00:52:25,765
[Sayagues] That was a magic trick.

942
00:52:25,851 --> 00:52:31,893
[Alvarez] Of course, at the beginning
after the ad, you could see that cooler...

943
00:52:33,442 --> 00:52:36,275
and that was another step forward
in the arc.

944
00:52:36,362 --> 00:52:39,650
[Luque] What are you doing?
Have you gone crazy? Your dog is in there.

945
00:52:42,993 --> 00:52:44,904
[Sayagues] A great thing here,

946
00:52:44,995 --> 00:52:47,532
is we just saw that
there's a difference between them.

947
00:52:47,623 --> 00:52:50,115
The blind guy couldn't kill the dog,
even though it was not his,

948
00:52:50,209 --> 00:52:53,747
but this guy, being its owner,
does not care.

949
00:52:53,837 --> 00:52:56,295
So they have quite different moral codes.

950
00:52:56,382 --> 00:53:01,127
[Alvarez] With the script,
we also wanted to raise the topic of...

951
00:53:02,221 --> 00:53:05,680
fatherhood, and who has--

952
00:53:05,766 --> 00:53:08,349
Whether or not you are entitled
to your children's love,

953
00:53:08,435 --> 00:53:12,099
in a story about this guy, the blind guy,

954
00:53:12,189 --> 00:53:14,055
who loves her
like she was his own daughter

955
00:53:14,149 --> 00:53:16,811
and takes care of her,
despite being such a monster.

956
00:53:16,902 --> 00:53:20,145
Takes better care of her as a father
than the other one,

957
00:53:20,239 --> 00:53:23,857
who is her real father,
but willing to kill her for his reasons.

958
00:53:23,951 --> 00:53:28,616
It was a question about who deserves
the affection of these children.

959
00:53:28,706 --> 00:53:30,447
So this guy with a dog,

960
00:53:30,541 --> 00:53:34,876
the story with the dog also represented
this same question.

961
00:53:34,962 --> 00:53:38,080
In a certain way, the dog's father,
who was Raylan,

962
00:53:38,173 --> 00:53:40,164
wouldn't hesitate to kill him,

963
00:53:40,259 --> 00:53:45,379
so the blind guy ends up being
a better father for that dog.

964
00:53:45,472 --> 00:53:49,340
At least he takes care of him
and eventually earns the dog's affection.

965
00:53:49,435 --> 00:53:54,271
-[Luque] Yes. It's the same thing.
-[Alvarez] And he'll save him.

966
00:53:54,356 --> 00:53:56,939
[Sayagues]
Here, fire is destroying the house,

967
00:53:57,025 --> 00:53:59,392
and he risks himself to set the dog free.

968
00:53:59,486 --> 00:54:02,148
[Alvarez] He risks his own life
to save this dog.

969
00:54:03,073 --> 00:54:06,031
We'll have to investigate
in another Don't Breathe story,

970
00:54:06,118 --> 00:54:10,487
when there are more movies,
what happened to him.

971
00:54:10,581 --> 00:54:13,539
Surely a dog saved his life at some point.

972
00:54:13,625 --> 00:54:16,583
-[Luque] Yes.
-[Alvarez] Sure, in war or somewhere.

973
00:54:16,670 --> 00:54:22,916
There must be a past story
that made him love animals so much.

974
00:54:23,010 --> 00:54:27,846
[Luque] Maybe through the loneliness
this character experienced

975
00:54:27,931 --> 00:54:31,640
when he lost his daughter,
maybe the dog helped him through it.

976
00:54:31,727 --> 00:54:33,638
The dog saved him, in a way.

977
00:54:33,729 --> 00:54:36,642
[Sayagues] That was a fantastic job
from the stuntmen

978
00:54:36,732 --> 00:54:39,565
who jumped head first like that,
just like you saw it.

979
00:54:40,360 --> 00:54:42,476
[Alvarez] Another reference to part one.

980
00:54:42,571 --> 00:54:45,188
[Sayagues] But the other way around.
It's his turn now to be up there.

981
00:54:45,282 --> 00:54:47,319
-[Luque] And much worse.
-[Sayagues] Yes.

982
00:54:47,409 --> 00:54:48,615
[Luque] With fire underneath.

983
00:54:48,702 --> 00:54:52,912
[Alvarez] He then remembered Alex
from the first movie, and was like, "Oh."

984
00:54:52,998 --> 00:54:55,581
But well, he was lucky enough
to fall on top of that.

985
00:54:55,667 --> 00:54:59,126
[Sayagues] This shot must be
the most epic shot in the whole movie

986
00:54:59,213 --> 00:55:02,456
because all the fire,
or most of it, is real.

987
00:55:02,549 --> 00:55:06,167
-[Luque] It's real.
-[Sayagues] So it was very time-consuming

988
00:55:06,261 --> 00:55:08,923
and all the Belgrade firemen were there,

989
00:55:09,014 --> 00:55:13,224
and everything was set up
for Stephen Lang to do this...

990
00:55:14,311 --> 00:55:16,894
with the house actually on fire.

991
00:55:16,980 --> 00:55:19,347
[Luque] Remember we struggled
to put that fire out?

992
00:55:19,441 --> 00:55:21,023
[Sayagues] Yes, yes.

993
00:55:21,109 --> 00:55:23,100
[Alvarez] You also set
the real set on fire, right?

994
00:55:23,195 --> 00:55:25,152
-[Luque and Sayagues] Yes.
-[Alvarez] It was useless.

995
00:55:25,239 --> 00:55:30,530
[Luque] Useless. It had windows
with bars that were on fire.

996
00:55:30,619 --> 00:55:34,078
[Alvarez] What I'd like to know
is if those were called flame bars.

997
00:55:34,164 --> 00:55:38,499
[Sayagues] No, look what it was.
Well, it was like that, but much larger

998
00:55:38,585 --> 00:55:41,293
and also the house caught on fire
in two minutes.

999
00:55:41,380 --> 00:55:42,791
[Alvarez] Of course, that's madness.

1000
00:55:42,798 --> 00:55:44,459
[Alvarez] Of course, that's madness.

1001
00:55:46,927 --> 00:55:48,338
[Luque] In Detroit.

1002
00:55:49,096 --> 00:55:52,179
[Alvarez] It's the third time
we've burned a house for our movies.

1003
00:55:52,266 --> 00:55:57,807
[Luque] Yeah, I have a lot of experience
with burning houses.

1004
00:55:57,896 --> 00:56:00,979
[Alvarez] The cabin caught fire.

1005
00:56:01,066 --> 00:56:03,524
The Girl in the Spider's Web
also ended with a burning house.

1006
00:56:03,610 --> 00:56:05,567
[Luque] That huge hotel, remember?

1007
00:56:05,654 --> 00:56:07,691
[Alvarez] We should've set
this one on fire.

1008
00:56:07,781 --> 00:56:09,442
[laughter]

1009
00:56:12,578 --> 00:56:14,160
This is Detroit, right?

1010
00:56:14,246 --> 00:56:16,829
-[Luque] Well, the exterior is.
-[Alvarez] Yeah, the exterior.

1011
00:56:16,915 --> 00:56:21,034
-[Sayagues] This is...
-[Luque] Close to the Latin Quarter.

1012
00:56:21,128 --> 00:56:23,540
[Sayagues] This is Serbia.
Yes, it's Serbia.

1013
00:56:23,630 --> 00:56:25,792
[Luque] Yes, it's a small town
called Arandelovac.

1014
00:56:25,883 --> 00:56:27,123
[Sayagues] Arandelovac.

1015
00:56:27,217 --> 00:56:29,834
[Alvarez] I saw that fish tank and said,
"Wow, that must explode."

1016
00:56:29,928 --> 00:56:31,669
[laughter]

1017
00:56:31,763 --> 00:56:35,882
Like every '90s movie,
if there's a fish tank...

1018
00:56:35,976 --> 00:56:38,638
[Luque] Those always explode
in slow motion.

1019
00:56:38,729 --> 00:56:41,471
[Alvarez] Showing a fish in the back
gasping for its last breath.

1020
00:56:41,565 --> 00:56:42,680
[Luque] Yes.

1021
00:56:46,445 --> 00:56:48,903
[Alvarez] This scene was longer.

1022
00:56:48,989 --> 00:56:54,359
We censored the original scene
in which Raylan showed her how to smoke.

1023
00:56:54,453 --> 00:56:56,069
[Luque] This image is amazing.

1024
00:56:56,163 --> 00:56:57,995
[Alvarez] I thought it was great,

1025
00:56:58,081 --> 00:57:01,619
because I felt it was
a good way of representing

1026
00:57:01,710 --> 00:57:05,499
the idea of, if you were thinking
that it wasn't that bad

1027
00:57:05,589 --> 00:57:09,878
that Raylan had taken her,
the worst scenario is bad parenting,

1028
00:57:09,968 --> 00:57:15,134
but you see he's showing her how to smoke
in the first scene. Off to a bad start!

1029
00:57:16,141 --> 00:57:17,302
Off to a bad start.

1030
00:57:19,019 --> 00:57:22,353
-But we did shoot it, right?
-[Sayagues] We did.

1031
00:57:22,439 --> 00:57:26,182
The scene ended up being too long
and it didn't get to the point.

1032
00:57:26,276 --> 00:57:31,567
The key is always to enter a scene
close to the point you need to make clear.

1033
00:57:31,657 --> 00:57:36,493
[Alvarez] Also I think the rating would
have killed us, we'd become NC-17.

1034
00:57:36,578 --> 00:57:38,569
[Sayagues]
Yes, it was sort of troublesome.

1035
00:57:39,498 --> 00:57:42,786
[Alvarez] Although, in Stand By Me,
there is a boy smoking.

1036
00:57:42,876 --> 00:57:47,245
[Luque] Those times were different.
People smoked inside a hospital.

1037
00:57:49,341 --> 00:57:50,752
What was my mother's name?

1038
00:57:50,842 --> 00:57:53,925
[Sayagues] I love how this scene turned
out, how the shots get narrowed.

1039
00:57:54,012 --> 00:57:56,754
She starts asking
increasingly intimate questions,

1040
00:57:56,848 --> 00:57:59,215
more relevant for her.

1041
00:57:59,309 --> 00:58:02,597
There's some sort of intimacy here.
I really like...

1042
00:58:02,688 --> 00:58:04,895
the way we shot from the sides.

1043
00:58:04,982 --> 00:58:07,223
[Luque] Yes, more and more closed.

1044
00:58:07,317 --> 00:58:09,900
[Sayagues] He touches her,
she lets him touch her,

1045
00:58:09,987 --> 00:58:12,729
like she's falling under his spell.

1046
00:58:12,823 --> 00:58:16,908
[Luque] She's falling into the spiderweb.
Remember what we said?

1047
00:58:16,994 --> 00:58:18,951
Everything that man told you is a lie.

1048
00:58:20,288 --> 00:58:21,949
What happened to him?

1049
00:58:22,040 --> 00:58:26,329
[Alvarez] Yes, it scares me to think where
the spider might be, it will show up soon

1050
00:58:26,420 --> 00:58:28,832
but it's around somewhere.

1051
00:58:28,922 --> 00:58:30,708
[Luque] Hanging from the ceiling.

1052
00:58:30,799 --> 00:58:34,963
[Alvarez]
See the excess of ramps in this room.

1053
00:58:35,053 --> 00:58:36,293
[laughter]

1054
00:58:36,388 --> 00:58:39,050
That's why it's there now.

1055
00:58:41,560 --> 00:58:42,971
Jesus.

1056
00:58:45,731 --> 00:58:49,599
We knew exactly what we were writing
up to this point.

1057
00:58:49,693 --> 00:58:54,278
From here on is
when we had a bunch of alternatives.

1058
00:58:54,364 --> 00:58:58,699
It always started here. I think the first
version was the one with the heart,

1059
00:58:58,785 --> 00:59:01,152
and everything
that's going to happen next.

1060
00:59:01,246 --> 00:59:04,659
Then we moved on
to two alternative versions

1061
00:59:04,750 --> 00:59:08,209
and then we went back to the one
with the heart, that was great.

1062
00:59:08,295 --> 00:59:12,505
And for the ones with a great memory,
those who remember that "wanted" face,

1063
00:59:12,591 --> 00:59:17,506
his face is on TV, on the news about...

1064
00:59:17,596 --> 00:59:19,086
[Luque] Organ trafficking.

1065
00:59:19,181 --> 00:59:22,219
-[Alvarez] Organ trafficking, right?
-[Sayagues] There's a man.

1066
00:59:22,309 --> 00:59:25,267
[Luque] That's the gang of bad guys
who are really bad.

1067
00:59:25,353 --> 00:59:26,969
[laughter]

1068
00:59:27,064 --> 00:59:30,398
But they were nice people.
With their criminal records.

1069
00:59:30,484 --> 00:59:32,566
[laughter]

1070
00:59:37,699 --> 00:59:40,157
[Alvarez] Genius. I think this moment is...

1071
00:59:40,243 --> 00:59:41,950
[Luque] Here's where everything goes away.

1072
00:59:42,037 --> 00:59:47,157
[Alvarez] An iconic scene of this saga.

1073
00:59:47,250 --> 00:59:50,788
It's like you convince yourself
her mother is dead,

1074
00:59:50,879 --> 00:59:55,669
but you don't realize the whole story
is a lie from the blind guy.

1075
00:59:55,759 --> 00:59:57,249
Until now.

1076
00:59:58,762 --> 01:00:00,344
She looks like Elvira.

1077
01:00:00,430 --> 01:00:02,717
[Luque] The one from The Addams Family.

1078
01:00:02,808 --> 01:00:04,469
[laughter]

1079
01:00:07,646 --> 01:00:09,512
[Alvarez] The mother's good.
Who's the actress?

1080
01:00:09,606 --> 01:00:12,064
[Sayagues] Fiona. She's amazing.

1081
01:00:12,150 --> 01:00:16,394
She spent just one week
doing the few scenes she had,

1082
01:00:16,488 --> 01:00:18,980
but the truth is
something unbelievable happened,

1083
01:00:19,074 --> 01:00:21,190
that didn't happen before during filming.

1084
01:00:21,284 --> 01:00:24,777
Every time she was on set
and every time she performed,

1085
01:00:24,871 --> 01:00:28,865
there was a deathly silence
because everyone was mesmerized by her.

1086
01:00:28,959 --> 01:00:32,042
-Everyone stared at the monitor.
-[Luque] It was amazing.

1087
01:00:32,129 --> 01:00:35,667
[Sayagues] Her presence was magnetic.

1088
01:00:36,466 --> 01:00:41,882
[Alvarez] I had seen her in a series,
Utopia, a very good English series.

1089
01:00:42,764 --> 01:00:45,802
They've been trying to make
the American version for a long time.

1090
01:00:45,892 --> 01:00:50,181
I remember watching all the chapters
of the English version at one point

1091
01:00:50,272 --> 01:00:51,854
and she was so good there.

1092
01:00:52,774 --> 01:00:55,857
Here, she's perfect. She's amazing.

1093
01:00:55,944 --> 01:00:57,230
This shot is also very good.

1094
01:00:57,320 --> 01:01:01,939
The work with the light,
how she gradually appears.

1095
01:01:02,033 --> 01:01:04,149
You can't see her face up to that point.

1096
01:01:08,665 --> 01:01:11,498
This for me is the scariest moment
of the whole movie.

1097
01:01:11,585 --> 01:01:14,919
[Luque] Yes! It's the scariest moment.

1098
01:01:15,005 --> 01:01:16,416
[Alvarez] Maybe because
I know what's next.

1099
01:01:16,506 --> 01:01:19,043
If you don't know what's next, you can't...

1100
01:01:19,134 --> 01:01:22,752
But it's clear that this woman
won't bring anything good to the story.

1101
01:01:22,846 --> 01:01:24,462
[laughter]

1102
01:01:25,390 --> 01:01:29,224
Normally this would've--
In any other movie,

1103
01:01:29,311 --> 01:01:31,894
this scene would've been
a scene of reunion and hope.

1104
01:01:31,980 --> 01:01:37,646
She was reunited with her mother.
Heidi there with the mother...

1105
01:01:37,736 --> 01:01:42,025
And you know from the way it's filmed

1106
01:01:42,115 --> 01:01:48,703
that clearly nothing good is going to
come out of this union. Brilliant.

1107
01:01:48,788 --> 01:01:53,282
[Luque] Now, what nerve the mother has
to pull all these theatrics.

1108
01:01:53,376 --> 01:01:55,708
[Alvarez chuckles]
She's genuinely excited.

1109
01:01:55,795 --> 01:01:57,752
[Luque] No, she's totally excited.

1110
01:01:57,839 --> 01:02:00,456
[Alvarez] She appreciates her own life
more than her daughter's,

1111
01:02:00,550 --> 01:02:01,915
but she is excited.

1112
01:02:02,010 --> 01:02:06,174
I think she's more excited
to see hope that she will live...

1113
01:02:06,264 --> 01:02:07,425
[Luque] Right, selfishness.

1114
01:02:07,515 --> 01:02:09,722
[Alvarez] Yes, total selfishness.

1115
01:02:09,809 --> 01:02:11,345
[Sayagues] We also talked about...

1116
01:02:11,436 --> 01:02:13,473
[Luque] She also hugs her lovingly! Scary.

1117
01:02:13,563 --> 01:02:17,056
-[Alvarez] She hugs her inside her heart.
-[Luque] All those lies.

1118
01:02:17,150 --> 01:02:18,561
[Sayagues] We talked with Fiona.

1119
01:02:18,652 --> 01:02:19,858
[Alvarez] Like the Blind Man
crying over Cindy's murder

1120
01:02:19,861 --> 01:02:21,647
[Alvarez] Like the Blind Man
crying over Cindy's murder

1121
01:02:21,738 --> 01:02:25,572
in the first one, but he actually cries
because of what's inside her, the kid.

1122
01:02:25,659 --> 01:02:28,071
[Sayagues] What we talked about with Fiona
is that either way,

1123
01:02:28,161 --> 01:02:30,869
she's her biological daughter,
from her womb,

1124
01:02:30,956 --> 01:02:34,165
as we see in the photo,
so she's moved somehow.

1125
01:02:34,251 --> 01:02:36,583
Perhaps when she planned all this,

1126
01:02:36,670 --> 01:02:39,128
she didn't consider
that when she saw her in person,

1127
01:02:39,214 --> 01:02:44,209
she was going to be moved, so it makes her
more insane and conflicted,

1128
01:02:44,302 --> 01:02:47,169
and she has to go even more crazy
to be able to continue with the plan.

1129
01:02:47,264 --> 01:02:49,380
[Luque] Yes, she has to delve into...

1130
01:02:49,474 --> 01:02:52,887
[Alvarez] That's why at this moment
she starts coughing up the blood.

1131
01:02:52,978 --> 01:02:56,596
She reminds herself that, well...

1132
01:02:56,690 --> 01:02:58,021
[Luque] She has no other choice.

1133
01:02:59,150 --> 01:03:01,391
[Alvarez] This couple, for me,
is one that--

1134
01:03:01,486 --> 01:03:04,319
On Halloween,
I want to dress up like them.

1135
01:03:04,406 --> 01:03:06,022
[laughter]

1136
01:03:06,116 --> 01:03:09,529
[Luque] Bonnie and Clyde.
Everything goes wrong.

1137
01:03:11,037 --> 01:03:14,075
[Alvarez] No, because I really believe
the love between the two of them.

1138
01:03:14,165 --> 01:03:16,122
There is no doubt that they are in love.

1139
01:03:16,209 --> 01:03:19,998
They make a great couple on screen,
very good.

1140
01:03:20,088 --> 01:03:21,078
[Luque] Yes.

1141
01:03:21,172 --> 01:03:22,958
[Alvarez] He'll do anything for her.

1142
01:03:23,049 --> 01:03:25,165
[Luque] He's madly in love with her.

1143
01:03:25,260 --> 01:03:28,378
[Sayagues] He's a prisoner of the spell,
too.

1144
01:03:28,471 --> 01:03:31,133
[Alvarez] Right.
